  {
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Hi @vaughn-taylor thanks for the example it helps a lot to understand the issue. The first problem that cause the map to not showing up is that Google Maps requires to set a height on the element where the map will be attached. We don't provide a default value for this because it can be hard to override. By adding this line of CSS the map should be displayed.\r\n\r\n```css\r\n#map {\r\n  height: 350px;\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nBut it will not display the results because the current widget doesn't support multiple locations for the `_geoloc` attribute. This is a limitation for now, I've opened [an issue](https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch.js/issues/2838) about that. A possible solution is to duplicate the records where you have multiple locations in order to have a single location for each of you records. Then you can use the `distinct` attribute to deduplicate your results. You can find more details about that [in our documentation](https://www.algolia.com/doc/guides/ranking/distinct). With this data structure you will be able to use the Geo Search widget.",
